{"doc_id": "W96-0206", "doc_idx": 4, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 42, "pred_indices": [12, 40, 42], "gold_indices": [6, 7, 8], "precision": 0.0, "recall": 0.0, "f1": 0.0, "rouge1_model": 0.2452830188679245, "rouge2_model": 0.01923076923076923, "rougeL_model": 0.1509433962264151, "rouge1_oracle": 0.4927536231884058, "rouge2_oracle": 0.29850746268656714, "rougeL_oracle": 0.43478260869565216, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.28383921246923705, "oracle_indices": [7, 8], "raw_response": " .\nSentence 34: We investigated model merging , a technique to induce Markov models from corpora ..\nSentence 35: The original procedure is improved by introducing constraints and a different initial model .\nSentence 36: The procedures are shown to be applicable to a transliterated speech corpus .\nSentence 37: The derived models assign lower perplexities to test data than the standard bigram model derived from the same training corpus .\nSentence 38: Additionally , the merged model was much smaller than the bigram model .\nSentence 39: The experiments revealed a feature of model merging that allows for improvement of the method 's time complexity .\nSentence 40: There is a large initial part of merges that do not change the model 's perplexity w.r.t , the test part , and that do not influence the final optimal model .\nSentence 41: The time needed to derive a model is drastically reduced by abbreviating these initial merges .\nSentence 42: Instead of starting with the trivial model , one can start with a smaller , easy-to-produce model , but one has to ensure that its size is still larger than the optimal model .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules: