{"doc_id": "P13-1116", "doc_idx": 5, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 58, "pred_indices": [7, 13, 22, 23], "gold_indices": [7, 22], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 1.0, "f1": 0.6666666666666666, "rouge1_model": 0.33999999999999997, "rouge2_model": 0.24489795918367344, "rougeL_model": 0.27999999999999997, "rouge1_oracle": 0.6296296296296297, "rouge2_oracle": 0.4615384615384615, "rougeL_oracle": 0.40740740740740744, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.12740740740740747, "oracle_indices": [7, 30], "raw_response": " new deterministic algorithm , ImpAr , that obtains very competitive and robust performances with respect to supervised approaches .\nSentence 50: That is , it can be applied where there is no available manual annotations to train .\nSentence 51: The code of this algorithm is publicly available and can be applied to any document .\nSentence 52: As input it only needs the document with explicit semantic role labeling and Super-Sense annotations .\nSentence 53: These annotations can be easily obtained from plain text using available tools7 , what makes this algorithm the first effective tool available for implicit SRL .\nSentence 54: As it can be easily seen , ImpAr has a large margin for improvement .\nSentence 55: For instance , providing more accurate spans for the fillers .\nSentence 56: We also plan to test alternative approaches to solve the arguments without explicit antecedents .\nSentence 57: For instance , our system can also profit from additional annotations like coreference , that has proved its utility in previous works .\nSentence 58: Finally , we also plan to study our approach on different languages and datasets ( for instance , the SemEval-2010 dataset ) .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences 