{"doc_id": "2022.naacl-main.154", "doc_idx": 7, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 48, "pred_indices": [2, 12, 16, 17], "gold_indices": [16, 17, 18, 37], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 0.5, "f1": 0.5, "rouge1_model": 0.1904761904761905, "rouge2_model": 0.03614457831325301, "rougeL_model": 0.13095238095238096, "rouge1_oracle": 0.25396825396825395, "rouge2_oracle": 0.06557377049180328, "rougeL_oracle": 0.22222222222222224, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.09126984126984128, "oracle_indices": [17], "raw_response": " on the original downstream data .\nSentence 40: Note that , while our evaluations in this work are limited to BERT , this proposed compression method can be directly used to compress other Transformer-based NLP models .\nSentence 41: The main contributions of this paper are as follows :\nSentence 42: \u2022 Compression of the embedding layer using the Kronecker decomposition with very low computational overhead .\nSentence 43: We introduced a novel method for compressing Transformer-based language models that uses Kronecker decomposition for the compression of the embedding layer and the linear mappings within the Transformer blocks .\nSentence 44: The proposed framework was used to compress the BERT BASE model .\nSentence 45: We used a very light two-stage KD method to train the compressed model .\nSentence 46: We show that the proposed framework can significantly reduce the size and the number of computations while outperforming stateof-the-art .\nSentence 47: The proposed method can be directly applied for compression of other Transformer-based language models .\nSentence 48: The combination of the proposed method with other compression techniques such layer truncation , pruning and quantization can be an interesting direction for future work .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```json\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2, 12, 16, 17]}\n```\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [2,"}
