{"doc_id": "P13-1066", "doc_idx": 9, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 45, "pred_indices": [18, 41], "gold_indices": [5, 6, 7, 18], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 0.25, "f1": 0.3333333333333333, "rouge1_model": 0.22448979591836735, "rouge2_model": 0.0625, "rougeL_model": 0.20408163265306126, "rouge1_oracle": 0.358974358974359, "rouge2_oracle": 0.10526315789473685, "rougeL_oracle": 0.30769230769230765, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.1036106750392464, "oracle_indices": [18, 7], "raw_response": ". , people who often agree with each other are likely to belong to the same camp .\nSentence 38: The proposed framework also facilitates tracking users ' ideology shifts and the resulting arguing nature .\nSentence 39: The proposed methods have been evaluated both qualitatively and quantitatively using a large number of real-life discussion / debate posts from four domains .\nSentence 40: Experimental results show that the proposed model is highly effective in performing its tasks and outperforms several baselines .\nSentence 41: This paper studied the problem of modeling user pair interactions in online discussions with the purpose of discovering the interaction or arguing nature of each author pair and various ADexpressions emitted in debates .\nSentence 42: A novel technique was also proposed to rank n-gram phrases where relevance based ranking was used in conjunction with a semi-supervised generative model .\nSentence 43: This method enables us to find better ADexpressions .\nSentence 44: Experiments using real-life online debate data showed the effectiveness of the model .\nSentence 45: In our future work , we intend to extend the model to account for stances , and issue specific interactions which would pave the way for user profiling and behavioral modeling .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   