{"doc_id": "2022.acl-long.480", "doc_idx": 11, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 42, "pred_indices": [11, 12, 13, 21], "gold_indices": [7, 11, 12, 13], "precision": 0.75, "recall": 0.75, "f1": 0.75, "rouge1_model": 0.2903225806451613, "rouge2_model": 0.13114754098360654, "rougeL_model": 0.25806451612903225, "rouge1_oracle": 0.4255319148936171, "rouge2_oracle": 0.17777777777777778, "rougeL_oracle": 0.3829787234042554, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.12491420727522312, "oracle_indices": [12], "raw_response": " is able to take into account longer context information than its unidirectional counterpart , while keeping the same training efficiency .\nSentence 37: Our proposed MT system has been evaluated under a realistic streaming setting being able to reach similar translation quality than a state-of-theart segmentation-free streaming MT system at a fraction of its latency .\nSentence 38: Additionally , our system has been shown to be competitive when compared with state-of-the-art simultaneous MT systems optimized for sentence-level translation , obtaining excellent results using a single model across a wide range of latency levels , thanks to its flexible inference policy .\nSentence 39: In terms of future work , additional training and inference procedures that take advantage of the streaming history in streaming MT are still open for research .\nSentence 40: One important avenue of improvement is to devise more robust training methods , so that simultaneous models can perform as well as their offline counterparts when carrying out inference at higher latencies .\nSentence 41: The segmentation model , though proved useful in a streaming setup , adds complexity and can greatly affect translation quality .\nSentence 42: Thus , the development of segmentation-free streaming MT models is another interesting research topic .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map 