{"doc_id": "E14-1023", "doc_idx": 14, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 43, "pred_indices": [9, 18, 21, 40], "gold_indices": [6, 8], "precision": 0.0, "recall": 0.0, "f1": 0.0, "rouge1_model": 0.1804511278195489, "rouge2_model": 0.030534351145038163, "rougeL_model": 0.07518796992481204, "rouge1_oracle": 0.5714285714285714, "rouge2_oracle": 0.3529411764705882, "rougeL_oracle": 0.4571428571428571, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.38195488721804505, "oracle_indices": [8], "raw_response": "4 , we present semantic features and tree kernel representations designed for the tasks .\nSentence 35: In Section 5 , we briefly review tree kernels and support vector machines ( SVM ) .\nSentence 36: In Section 6 we present experiments and discuss the results .\nSentence 37: In Section 7 we discuss related work .\nSentence 38: We conclude and give future directions of work in Section 8 .\nSentence 39: This work has only scratched the surface of possibilities for using frame semantic features and tree structures for the task of social event extraction .\nSentence 40: We have shown that tree kernels are well suited to work with possibly inaccurate semantic parses in contrast to hand-crafted features that require the semantic parses to be completely accurate .\nSentence 41: We have also extended our previous work by designing and evaluating a full system for social network extraction .\nSentence 42: A more natural data representation for semantic parses is a graph structure .\nSentence 43: We are actively exploring the design of semantic graph structures that may be brought to bear with the use of graph kernels ( Vishwanathan et al . , 2010 ) .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [9, 18, 21, 40]}\n```</thought>\n```json"}
