{"doc_id": "D19-1240", "doc_idx": 15, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 45, "pred_indices": [2, 12, 17, 24], "gold_indices": [1, 2, 10, 12, 15, 16], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 0.3333333333333333, "f1": 0.4, "rouge1_model": 0.29787234042553196, "rouge2_model": 0.021739130434782608, "rougeL_model": 0.1702127659574468, "rouge1_oracle": 0.37500000000000006, "rouge2_oracle": 0.043478260869565216, "rougeL_oracle": 0.33333333333333337, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.16312056737588657, "oracle_indices": [12, 3], "raw_response": "t .\nSentence 36: a given task , and\nSentence 37: ( 3 ) we conduct experiments on real-world data to demonstrate the effectiveness of RLTA in an important natural language processing task .\nSentence 38: In this paper , we propose a deep reinforcement learning based text anonymization , RLTA , which creates a text embedding such that does not leak user 's private-attribute information while preserving its utility w.r.t .\nSentence 39: a given task .\nSentence 40: RLTA has two main components : ( 1 ) an attention based taskaware text representation learner , and ( 2 ) a deep RL based privacy and utility preserver .\nSentence 41: Our results illustrate the effectiveness of RLTA in preserving privacy and utility .\nSentence 42: One future direction is to generate privacy preserving text rather than embeddings .\nSentence 43: We also adopt deep Q-learning to train the agent .\nSentence 44: A future direction is to apply different RL algorithms and investigate how it impacts results .\nSentence 45: It would be also interesting to adopt RLTA for other types of data .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST