{"doc_id": "N12-1085", "doc_idx": 19, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 44, "pred_indices": [1, 2, 16, 38], "gold_indices": [1, 2], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 1.0, "f1": 0.6666666666666666, "rouge1_model": 0.3870967741935484, "rouge2_model": 0.27868852459016397, "rougeL_model": 0.3870967741935484, "rouge1_oracle": 0.631578947368421, "rouge2_oracle": 0.4594594594594595, "rougeL_oracle": 0.631578947368421, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.24448217317487264, "oracle_indices": [1, 2], "raw_response": "36: A solution to the problem of modeling these structures requires the development of new techniques that model complex linguistic relationships in an application-dependent way .\nSentence 37: We have shown that we can mine these relationships without being overcome by the data-sparsity issues that typically stymie learning over complex linguistic structure .\nSentence 38: The limitations on these techniques ultimately find their root in the difficulty in modeling complex syntactic structures that simultaneously exclude irrelevant portions of the structure while maintaining connected relations .\nSentence 39: Our technique uses a structurelabelling scheme that enforces connectedness .\nSentence 40: Enforcing connected structure is not only necessary to produce useful results but also to improve accuracy .\nSentence 41: Further performance gains might be possible by enriching the feature set .\nSentence 42: For example , the POS tagset used by the Stanford parser contains multiple verb tags that represent different English tenses and numbers .\nSentence 43: For the purpose of sentiment relations , it is possible that the differences between verb tags are too small to matter and are causing data sparsity issues .\nSentence 44: Thus , we could additional features that \" back off \" to general verb tags .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, 38]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [1, 2, 16, "}
