{"doc_id": "P10-1049", "doc_idx": 24, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 52, "pred_indices": [2, 26, 28, 32], "gold_indices": [1, 2], "precision": 0.25, "recall": 0.5, "f1": 0.3333333333333333, "rouge1_model": 0.23214285714285712, "rouge2_model": 0.05454545454545455, "rougeL_model": 0.10714285714285714, "rouge1_oracle": 0.6792452830188679, "rouge2_oracle": 0.4313725490196078, "rougeL_oracle": 0.6037735849056604, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.4966307277628032, "oracle_indices": [1], "raw_response": " phrase translation probabilities in a way that they are consistent with their use in translation .\nSentence 46: A crucial aspect here is the use of leaving-one-out to avoid over-fitting .\nSentence 47: We have shown that the technique is superior to limiting phrase lengths and smoothing with lexical probabilities alone .\nSentence 48: While models trained from Viterbi alignments already lead to good results , we have demonstrated that considering the 100-best alignments allows to better model the ambiguities in phrase segmentation .\nSentence 49: The proposed techniques are shown to be superior to previous approaches that only used lexical probabilities to smooth phrase tables or imposed limits on the phrase lengths .\nSentence 50: On the WMT08 Europarl task we show improvements of 0.9 BLEU points with the trained phrase table and 1.4 BLEU points when interpolating the newly trained model with the original , heuristically extracted phrase table .\nSentence 51: In TER , improvements are 0.4 and 1.7 points .\nSentence 52: In addition to the improved performance , the trained models are smaller leading to faster and smaller translation systems .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include th