{"doc_id": "N10-1045", "doc_idx": 26, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 21, "pred_indices": [6, 9, 10], "gold_indices": [5, 8, 9, 10], "precision": 0.6666666666666666, "recall": 0.5, "f1": 0.5714285714285715, "rouge1_model": 0.20512820512820512, "rouge2_model": 0.05194805194805195, "rougeL_model": 0.14102564102564102, "rouge1_oracle": 0.32989690721649484, "rouge2_oracle": 0.10526315789473685, "rougeL_oracle": 0.24742268041237112, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.10639703938673009, "oracle_indices": [10, 21], "raw_response": " NLP tasks .\nSentence 15: Among these , as a long-term goal , we plan to adopt CLTE to support the alignment of text portions that express the same meaning in different languages .\nSentence 16: As a possible application scenario , CLTE can be used to address content merging tasks in tidy multilingual environments , such as commercial Web sites , digital libraries , or user generated content collections .\nSentence 17: Within such framework , as it will be discussed in the last section of this paper , CLTE components can be used for automatic content synchronization in a concurrent , collaborative , and multilingual editing setting , e.g. Wikipedia .\nSentence 18: This paper presented a preliminary investigation towards cross-lingual Textual Entailment , focusing on possible research directions and alternative methodologies .\nSentence 19: Baseline results have been provided to demonstrate the potentialities of a simple approach that integrates MT and monolingual TE components .\nSentence 20: Overall , our work sets a novel framework for further studies and experiments to improve crosslingual NLP tasks .\nSentence 21: In particular , CLTE can be scaled to more complex problems , such as cross-lingual content merging and synchronization .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome)