{"doc_id": "N06-1029", "doc_idx": 27, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 44, "pred_indices": [2, 12, 26, 27], "gold_indices": [1, 2, 9, 24, 26, 28], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 0.3333333333333333, "f1": 0.4, "rouge1_model": 0.2647058823529412, "rouge2_model": 0.08955223880597016, "rougeL_model": 0.16176470588235295, "rouge1_oracle": 0.3793103448275862, "rouge2_oracle": 0.17857142857142855, "rougeL_oracle": 0.3793103448275862, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.21754563894523324, "oracle_indices": [2, 35], "raw_response": "0 % of supervised levels , and , where comparable , well above a good discriminative classifier trained on a comparably small set of labelled data .\nSentence 40: Unsupervised techniques achieve accuracies of 87 % on the cleanest read speech , reaching 57 % on data from a standard Mandarin broadcast news corpus , and over 78 % on pitch accent classification for English broadcast news .\nSentence 41: Semi-supervised classification in the Mandarin four-class classification task reaches 94 % accuracy on read speech , 70 % on broadcast news data , improving dramatically over both the simple baseline of 25 % and a standard SVM with an RBF kernel trained only on the labeled examples .\nSentence 42: Future work will consider a broader range of tone and intonation classification , including the richer tone set of Cantonese as well as Bantu family tone languages , where annotated data truly is very rare .\nSentence 43: We also hope to integrate a richer contextual representation of tone and intonation consistent with phonetic theory within this unsupervised and semisupervised learning framework .\nSentence 44: We will further explore improvements in classification accuracy based on increases in labeled and unlabeled training examples .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude 