{"doc_id": "P11-1119", "doc_idx": 32, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 33, "pred_indices": [1, 2, 7, 13], "gold_indices": [1, 2, 6, 7, 13, 25, 26], "precision": 1.0, "recall": 0.5714285714285714, "f1": 0.7272727272727273, "rouge1_model": 0.3021582733812949, "rouge2_model": 0.23357664233576644, "rougeL_model": 0.28776978417266186, "rouge1_oracle": 0.6511627906976745, "rouge2_oracle": 0.4390243902439025, "rougeL_oracle": 0.6046511627906976, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.3168813786180358, "oracle_indices": [1, 11], "raw_response": " expressions in humanhuman dialogue is widely recognized .\nSentence 27: Facial expressions offer a promising channel for understanding the emotions experienced by users of dialogue systems , particularly given the ubiquity of webcam technologies and the increasing number of dialogue systems that are deployed on webcamenabled devices .\nSentence 28: This paper has reported on a first step toward using knowledge of user facial expressions to improve a dialogue act classification model for tutorial dialogue , and the results demonstrate that facial expressions hold great promise for distinguishing the pedagogically relevant dialogue act REQUEST FOR FEEDBACK , and the conversational moves of GROUNDING .\nSentence 29: These early findings highlight the importance of future work in this area .\nSentence 30: Dialogue act classification models have not fully leveraged some of the techniques emerging from work on sentiment analysis .\nSentence 31: These approaches may prove particularly useful for identifying emotions in dialogue utterances .\nSentence 32: Another important direction for future work involves more fully exploring the ways in which affect expression differs between textual and spoken dialogue .\nSentence 33: Finally , as automatic facial tagging technologies mature , they may prove powerful enough to enable broadly deployed dialogue systems to feasibly leverage facial expression data in the near future .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each 