{"doc_id": "N10-1034", "doc_idx": 40, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 43, "pred_indices": [3, 11, 14, 26], "gold_indices": [1, 2, 3, 11, 12, 13, 14], "precision": 0.75, "recall": 0.42857142857142855, "f1": 0.5454545454545454, "rouge1_model": 0.22222222222222224, "rouge2_model": 0.07518796992481203, "rougeL_model": 0.16296296296296295, "rouge1_oracle": 0.5, "rouge2_oracle": 0.2631578947368421, "rougeL_oracle": 0.45, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.2870370370370371, "oracle_indices": [3], "raw_response": " first collection contains of 5.5 million parsed trees , two orders of magnitude larger than those used by existing tree query systems , while the second collection contains 26.5 million trees .\nSentence 38: We have shown how an IR engine can be used to build a high performance tree query system .\nSentence 39: It outperforms existing approaches using indexless inmemory search , or custom indexes , or relational database systems , or XML database systems .\nSentence 40: We reported the results of a variety of experiments to demonstrate the efficiency of query for a variety of query types on two treebanks consisting of around 5 and 26 million sentences , more than two orders of magnitude larger than what existing systems support .\nSentence 41: The approach is quite general , and not limited to particular treebank formats or query languages .\nSentence 42: This work suggests that web-scale tree query may soon be feasible .\nSentence 43: This opens the door to some interesting possibilities : augmenting web search with syntactic constraints , the ability discover rare examples of particular syntactic constructions , and as a technique for garnering better statistics and more sensitive features for the purpose of constructing language models .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [3, 11, 14, 26]}\n```/////////////</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [3, 11, 14, 26]}\n```/\n"}
