{"doc_id": "P16-1218", "doc_idx": 52, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 30, "pred_indices": [10, 11, 12, 17], "gold_indices": [11, 15, 17], "precision": 0.5, "recall": 0.6666666666666666, "f1": 0.5714285714285715, "rouge1_model": 0.3035714285714286, "rouge2_model": 0.18181818181818182, "rougeL_model": 0.2142857142857143, "rouge1_oracle": 0.3404255319148936, "rouge2_oracle": 0.2222222222222222, "rougeL_oracle": 0.3404255319148936, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.1261398176291793, "oracle_indices": [17], "raw_response": " which distributed representation of sentence segment is learned by using subtraction between LSTM hidden vectors .\nSentence 24: Experiment shows this further enhances our model 's ability to access to sentence-level information .\nSentence 25: \u2022 Last but important , our model is a first-order model using standard Eisner algorithm for decoding , the computational cost remains at the lowest level among graph-based models .\nSentence 26: Our model does not trade-off efficiency for accuracy .\nSentence 27: We evaluate our model on the English Penn Treebank and Chinese Penn Treebank , experiments show that our model achieves competitive parsing accuracy compared with conventional high-order models , however , with a much lower computational cost .\nSentence 28: In this paper , we propose an LSTM-based neural network model for graph-based dependency parsing .\nSentence 29: Utilizing Bidirectional LSTM and segment embeddings learned by LSTM-Minus allows our model access to sentence-level information , making our model more accurate in recovering longdistance dependencies with only first-order factorization .\nSentence 30: Experiments on PTB and CTB show that our model could be competitive with conventional high-order models with a faster speed .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```jsonjsonjson\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```jsonjson\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```json\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```json\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```json\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```json\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [10, 11, 12, 17]}\n```</"}
