{"doc_id": "E99-1005", "doc_idx": 60, "aspect": "challenge", "num_sentences": 29, "pred_indices": [14, 26, 29], "gold_indices": [11, 12], "precision": 0.0, "recall": 0.0, "f1": 0.0, "rouge1_model": 0.10619469026548672, "rouge2_model": 0.018018018018018014, "rougeL_model": 0.08849557522123894, "rouge1_oracle": 0.2631578947368421, "rouge2_oracle": 0.1111111111111111, "rougeL_oracle": 0.2631578947368421, "oracle_gap_rougeL": 0.17466231951560315, "oracle_indices": [20], "raw_response": " pair ( operationalised by corpus co-occurrence frequency ) .\nSentence 22: In a correlation analysis we compared judged plausibility with the predictions of five corpus-based variables .\nSentence 23: The highest correlation was obtained with the co-occurrence frequency of the adjective-noun pair .\nSentence 24: Conditional probability , the log-likelihood ratio , and Resnik 's ( 1993 ) selectional association measure were also significantly correlated with plausibility ratings .\nSentence 25: The correlation with Resnik 's measure was negative , contrary to the predictions of his model .\nSentence 26: This points to a problem with his technique for estimating word class frequencies , which is aggravated by the collocational nature of noun-adjective combinations .\nSentence 27: Overall , the results confirm the strongly lexicalist and collocational nature of adjective-noun combinations .\nSentence 28: This fact could be exploited in a generation system by taking into account corpus co-occurrence counts for adjective-noun pairs ( which can be obtained straightforwardly ) during lexical choice .\nSentence 29: Future research has to identify how this approach can be generalised to unseen data .\n\nInstructions:\n1. For each sentence, think step-by-step (internally):\n   a. Identify the key claim or information the sentence conveys.\n   b. Map it to one of the three aspects (challenge / approach / outcome).\n   c. Conclude whether it matches \"challenge\": Yes or No.\n2. Select the sentences concluded Yes.\nDo not include the reasoning in the final output.\n\nRules:\n- Select AT MOST 4 sentences for the \"challenge\" aspect.\n- If no sentences match, return an empty list.\n- Indices are 1-based.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON.\n\nReturn format:\n{\"selected_sentences\": [list_of_sentence_numbers]}\nmodel\nthought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```thought\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought>\n```json\n{\"selected_sentences\": [14, 26, 29]}\n```</thought"}
